"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 25–27
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1samuel-25-27.py

Ch25: Nabal/Abigail — the rejected provision-giver; Abigail as intercessor;
      David's restraint entrusting vengeance to YHWH; the vindication of the innocent
Ch26: Second sparing of Saul — the patient innocent sufferer; the theology of the
      LORD's anointed; David as model for Christ's response to unjust suffering
Ch27: David at Gath — exile before kingship; the liminal period before enthronement;
      the moral complexity of the type and its limits

Christological classification notes:
- David's restraint from vengeance is consistently classified as 'shadow' — it
  anticipates 1 Pet 2:23 but David is not the innocent sinless sufferer Christ is
- Abigail's intercession is a 'theme' — not a type of Christ but of the intercessor role
- The LORD's anointed theology in ch 26 is a 'direct' OT-to-NT connection (Acts 10:38)
- David's Philistine exile is 'theme' — the pattern of the elect passing through foreign
  territory/suffering before enthronement
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "25": {
    "1": "<p>Samuel's death closes the prophetic chapter of Israel's history that prepared for the Davidic kingship. His burial at Ramah ends the ministry of the man who declared the LORD's rejection of Saul and privately anointed David — the prophet whose word created the conditions for the coming king. The pattern of prophetic preparation followed by the prophet's removal before the king's arrival is repeated in the NT: John the Baptist, the last of the OT prophets, dies before Jesus's public enthronement begins. Both Samuel and John the Baptist are forerunners whose departure makes room for the anointed one they heralded (John 3:30 — 'he must increase, but I must decrease'). The narrative of Israel's preparation for its true king passes through the death of each preparatory voice.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The setting — a wealthy man in Maon whose property is in Carmel — establishes the social and economic landscape into which David's request enters. The chapter will turn on the contrast between Nabal's enormous wealth and his absolute unwillingness to give. This contrast is itself a revelation of God's character: the narrative is preparing to show that true wealth, rightly administered, flows from the one who gave it — and that hoarding it in the face of legitimate need constitutes a kind of covenant rebellion. The theme of abundant provision withheld by the stingy landowner recurs in Jesus's parable of the rich fool (Luke 12:16-21): 'You fool! This night your soul is required of you' — the same verdict the narrative will deliver on Nabal (v37-38).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The pairing of Nabal (fool/impious) and Abigail (my father rejoices) names the two spiritual postures the chapter will explore: the rejection of wisdom and the embodiment of it. In the wisdom tradition the fool (<em>nābāl</em>) is the one who says in his heart 'there is no God' (Ps 14:1 uses the same root) — practical atheism that refuses to acknowledge covenant obligation. Abigail, whose name evokes the Father's joy, is the character who will act in alignment with YHWH's purposes when the fool refuses. She does not carry explicit Messianic weight but participates in the wisdom trajectory: Proverbs 8, the personified Wisdom who 'was beside him, like a master workman' (v30), casts a shadow on all figures who embody covenant wisdom in the face of folly.</p>",
    "4": "<p>This verse establishes the narrative situation. The broader christological frame is that David the anointed king is in the wilderness, sustaining his band while waiting for the kingship YHWH has promised — a pattern that recurs in Jesus's wilderness period (Matt 4:1-11), and in the entire apostolic age: the church awaits the full enthronement of its king while living in the wilderness of the present age. The feast (sheepshearing) into which David is about to send his request is the occasion of refused welcome — the rejected king at the door of one who owns everything.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David sends his messengers 'in his name' — an act of self-presentation to a host who should have recognized the claim. The rejected provision-request is a shadow of the pattern that the Gospel of John will develop into the central tragedy of the Incarnation: 'He came to his own, and his own people did not receive him' (John 1:11). The request David makes through proper channels — approaching the feast with a formal delegation, speaking in the protocols of covenant hospitality — mirrors the formal approach of the divine claim on covenant people who refuse to honor it.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The threefold peace-greeting — <em>šālôm</em> to the man, his household, and all that he has — invokes the fullness of covenant blessing. In the Gospel narrative, the disciples are instructed to greet households with the same formula: 'Into whatever house you enter, first say &ldquo;Peace be to this house&rdquo;' (Luke 10:5). If the peace is received, it rests on that house; if refused, it returns to the one who offered it (Luke 10:6). Nabal's refusal of the peace-greeting will demonstrate this: the peace that he should have received returns to David as a blessing, while the judgment Abigail averts falls on Nabal instead.</p>",
    "7": "<p>David's claim — his men protected Nabal's shepherds and took nothing — is the record of unrequited service. The pattern of service rendered without appropriate recognition or return is the shape of every prophetic and messianic rejection narrative: the servants sent to the vineyard who are beaten and sent away (Matt 21:33-41). David's account of good service unacknowledged is the immediate context that makes Nabal's dismissal so theologically weighted: the one who protected, rather than preying on, Nabal's flocks is being equated with a runaway slave. The Servant of Isaiah 53 performs the same unrequited labor: 'He was despised and rejected by men' after having borne 'our griefs and carried our sorrows.'</p>",
    "8": "<p>David appeals to the festive occasion and Nabal's social obligation. The appeal to <em>yôm ṭôb</em> (good day/feast) as the context for asking reflects the covenant structure in which abundance creates obligation. The refusal to give on a feast day is a refusal to participate in the covenant economy of blessing — the same dynamic Jesus will diagnose in the Pharisees who give tithes of mint and dill but neglect the weightier matters of the law (Matt 23:23). Nabal's feast-day hoarding is not incidental to the Christological narrative: it is the portrait of a religious economy that keeps all the forms without the substance of covenant generosity.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The messengers deliver the words faithfully and wait. The act of faithful delivery and waiting for response is the posture of every prophet and apostle who has borne the word of the LORD and awaited Israel's answer. The narrative of Israel's rejection of her prophets and messengers culminates in Jesus's parable: 'the servants of the landowner who were beaten, killed, and stoned — and finally the son himself' (Matt 21:35-39). Nabal's dismissal of David's messengers stands in this sequence.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Nabal's refusal — 'Who is David? Who is the son of Jesse?' — is the articulate rejection of the anointed. He knows exactly who David is (his men know, his servants know) and chooses not to recognize him. The rhetoric of unrecognition — 'who is this man?' — is the repeated posture of those who encounter the Messiah and refuse his claim. The crowds at Gethsemane ask 'who is this?' The Sanhedrin asks 'are you the Christ?' Pilate asks 'are you the king of the Jews?' Nabal's dismissal is the local, narrative-level version of the Christological unrecognition that runs through the Gospels: knowing who the claimant is and choosing not to honor the claim.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Nabal's rhetorical question — 'Should I take my bread, my water, my meat, and give it to men I do not know?' — expresses the logic of closed covenant: resources belong to their possessor and no obligation extends outward. This is the logic that Jesus specifically overturns in the feeding of the 5,000 (John 6:5-13: 'Where are we to buy bread, so that these people may eat?' — and five loaves feed five thousand with twelve baskets left over), and in the washing of the disciples' feet. The economy of the kingdom operates on the opposite principle: what is given freely multiplies; what is hoarded is lost (the parable of talents, Matt 25:14-30). Nabal is the figure of the closed economy; Christ is the figure of the open one.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The messengers return and report everything. Their faithfulness stands in contrast to Nabal's refusal. The narrative is setting up the crisis that will require divine intervention — the same structural movement in which human rejection triggers the need for a greater act. Just as Israel's rejection of the prophets created the conditions that required the Son himself to come, Nabal's rejection of David's messengers creates the crisis that brings Abigail onto the stage as the decisive actor.</p>",
    "13": "<p>David arms 400 men with swords and moves toward Nabal's household with the intent to destroy every male. The anointed king, provoked beyond restraint, moves toward vengeance — and is about to do exactly what he will later acknowledge (v33-34) would have been wrong. This is one of the narrative's most honest portraits of the type's limitation: David is not yet the sinless sufferer, and his impulse to violent self-vindication is real and sinful. The chapter requires divine intervention precisely because the human type (David) cannot embody perfect patience under injustice. That is left for the antitype: 'when he was reviled, he did not revile in return; when he suffered, he did not threaten, but continued entrusting himself to him who judges justly' (1 Pet 2:23).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The servant's report to Abigail initiates the providential chain. It is a servant — the lowest in the household — who grasps the danger and knows where wisdom resides. The inversion of the expected social order — the insignificant servant acting while the powerful fool fails — is consistent with the kingdom pattern Jesus describes: 'God has chosen what is foolish in the world to shame the wise... what is low and despised in the world, even things that are not, to bring to nothing things that are' (1 Cor 1:27-28).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The servant's testimony — 'those men were very good to us; we were not harmed and nothing went missing' — is an honest witness to unrequited service. The narrative structurally parallels the testimony to Jesus's character that repeatedly comes from those on the periphery of the rejection: the Roman centurion ('truly this was the Son of God,' Matt 27:54), the thief on the cross ('this man has done nothing wrong,' Luke 23:41), Pilate's wife ('have nothing to do with that righteous man,' Matt 27:19). Those who have actually experienced the service of the rejected one bear honest witness to it.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The 'wall of protection' metaphor — night and day — carries forward the divine protection imagery that runs through Israel's wilderness tradition: YHWH as a wall of fire by night and pillar of cloud by day (Exod 13:21). David's men provide exactly this kind of comprehensive, tireless covering — but without recognition or return. The theme of unrecognized protective service is the shape of Israel's history with its prophets, and of the world's history with its Messiah: 'He was in the world, and the world was made through him, yet the world did not know him' (John 1:10).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The servant's verdict on Nabal — 'no one can speak to him' — is the diagnosis of the hardened heart that the prophets repeatedly named in Israel: 'They made their hearts diamond-hard lest they should hear the law and the words that the LORD of hosts had sent by his Spirit through the former prophets' (Zech 7:12). The hardness that refuses all counsel is the spiritual condition of the covenant community that cannot receive the word of correction — the same hardness Jesus diagnoses in the generation that killed the prophets and will reject him (Matt 23:37: 'O Jerusalem, Jerusalem... how often would I have gathered your children... but you were not willing').</p>",
    "18": "<p>Abigail's provision — assembled rapidly and sent ahead to meet David — is an act of covenant generosity that stands in radical contrast to Nabal's refusal. The list of provisions (bread, wine, sheep, grain, raisins, figs) is a feast-abundance offered freely, without negotiation. The theme of abundant free provision is one of the most consistent registers of the kingdom of God: the wedding feast (Matt 22:1-14), the father's robe and ring and fatted calf for the returning son (Luke 15:22-24), the breakfast Jesus prepares on the beach for the disciples (John 21:12-13). Abigail's provision does not typify Christ but embodies the covenant economy that Christ will embody definitively.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Abigail acts without telling Nabal — not deception but emergency wisdom. She moves through the landscape of crisis without the false covering of a fool's approval. This is the pattern of the wise actor in the apocalyptic literature: 'the one on the housetop must not go down to take what is in his house... flee to the mountains' (Matt 24:17-18). Decisive action without waiting for the approval of those who cannot see the crisis is itself a form of faithfulness to the situation YHWH has created.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The providential encounter — Abigail coming down the hidden path at the exact moment David and his armed men are descending — is a divine arrangement. The narrative signals this by structuring the scene as an unexpected crossing of paths: neither party set out to meet the other. The theology of providential timing — the right word, the right person, the right moment — is the theology of the Incarnation: 'when the fullness of time had come, God sent forth his Son' (Gal 4:4). YHWH arranges the meeting that prevents the bloodshed David is about to commit.</p>",
    "21": "<p>David's soliloquy — 'I have been guarding everything this man has for nothing' — gives voice to the experience of unrequited service that the righteous servant knows. The bitterness that approaches and that he later renounces is the moment where the type's limitation is starkest: David has not yet learned to entrust the outcome fully to YHWH. He is a man of genuine faith who nonetheless reaches the edge of violent self-vindication. The contrast with Christ is deliberate and instructive: 'He was in the form of God, did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped... humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death' (Phil 2:6-8). David approaches the edge but is pulled back; Christ never approaches it.</p>",
    "22": "<p>David's oath to destroy every male — the language of total judgment — reveals the depth of the crisis. A man who will later refuse to strike the LORD's anointed (ch. 24, 26) and who will weep over Saul and Absalom is here swearing an oath of household destruction over a social insult. This is the narrative's honest portrayal of why a human savior cannot be the final answer: the righteous man contains within himself the capacity for unjust violence. The oath is never fulfilled — YHWH intervenes — but its formulation is itself the evidence that David needs a redeemer, not just victories. Only the sinless Son of Man can be the ultimate champion.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Abigail's prostration before David — full, immediate, complete — is the posture of intercession. She inserts herself physically between David's wrath and its object. The intercessory posture of standing between judgment and its target is one of the most consistent OT images of what Christ does on the cross: 'He bore the sin of many and makes intercession for the transgressors' (Isa 53:12). Abigail is not a type of Christ in the full sense — she is a wisdom figure, acting to protect her household from a legitimate (if impending) act of violence — but her bodily interposition embodies the logic of intercession that Christ will fulfill completely.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Abigail's formula — 'let the blame fall on me alone' — is the classic structure of vicarious liability: taking the guilt of another upon oneself to protect them from the consequence. The legal transfer of guilt is the structure of atonement theology. Abigail does not bear actual guilt; her assumption of liability is rhetorical and protective. Christ's assumption of guilt is real: 'God made him who knew no sin to be sin for us, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God' (2 Cor 5:21). The shape of the action is the same — the innocent assuming the position of the guilty to protect them — but the ontological reality is categorically different. Abigail's intercession points toward what it cannot fully embody.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Abigail's name-theology argument — 'his name is Nabal and folly is with him' — articulates the principle that a person's rejection of wisdom is self-defining and self-destroying. Nabal's hardened foolishness is not merely bad character but a kind of covenant death: the fool of Ps 14:1 ('the fool says in his heart there is no God') is the one who refuses to acknowledge his accountability to the Creator and Covenant Lord. The theme of folly-as-death and wisdom-as-life converges in Proverbs 8:35-36: 'Whoever finds me finds life... but he who fails to find me injures himself; all who hate me love death.' Abigail, embodying wisdom, is literally the life-choice before David; Nabal, embodying folly, brings death upon himself.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Abigail's theological assertion — 'the LORD has kept you from coming to bloodshed and from saving yourself by your own hand' — frames the entire encounter as divine restraint of the righteous man from sin. The phrase 'saving yourself by your own hand' (<em>hôšîaʿ yāḏᵉḵā lāḵ</em>) is the theological key: the temptation to self-salvation by force is the temptation that every anointed figure faces. Jesus faces it in the wilderness (Matt 4:1-11), in Gethsemane ('do you think I cannot appeal to my Father, and he will at once send me more than twelve legions of angels?' Matt 26:53), and on the cross ('come down from the cross, if you are the Son of God,' Matt 27:40). YHWH restrains David from this self-salvation; Christ voluntarily refuses it.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Abigail's gift — offered as a <em>bᵉrākāh</em> (blessing) for the young men — is freely given with no prior obligation on David's part. The gift that exceeds obligation, that gives without requiring a prior account of merit, is the structure of grace. The NT vocabulary of <em>charis</em> (grace/gift) names this same pattern: 'For you know the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, that though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor, so that you by his poverty might become rich' (2 Cor 8:9). The free provision of Abigail's gift to men who had no legal claim on it reflects the economy of divine grace that Christ's self-giving definitively establishes.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Abigail's prophetic declaration — 'the LORD will certainly establish a lasting house for my lord, because my lord is fighting the battles of the LORD' — is an oracle of Davidic election spoken before the Davidic covenant is formally announced (2 Sam 7). She articulates what the narrative has been building toward: David is not just a fugitive but YHWH's designated king, and his house will endure. This is the 'lasting house' (<em>bayit neʾĕmān</em>) promise that Nathan formalizes in 2 Sam 7:11-16 and that Paul identifies as the gospel: 'Of David's offspring God has brought to Israel a Savior, Jesus, as he promised' (Acts 13:23). Abigail speaks the election theology that runs from this wilderness scene to the throne of David to the birth in Bethlehem.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The 'bundle of the living' (<em>ṣᵉrôr haḥayyîm</em>) — the metaphor for YHWH binding the life of the righteous securely against loss — points forward to the divine preservation that guarantees the elect cannot be ultimately destroyed. The NT equivalent is the Johannine language of the Father's hand: 'My Father, who has given them to me, is greater than all, and no one is able to snatch them out of the Father's hand' (John 10:29). The enemies' lives, by contrast, are 'slung out' (<em>qelaʿ</em> — from a sling): the same instrument David used to defeat Goliath becomes a metaphor for the ejection of the wicked from the presence of YHWH. The bundle-and-sling contrast is an early expression of the two destinies that the Gospel will make explicit: preserved in the Father's hand or cast into the outer darkness.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Abigail's prophetic anticipation of David as 'ruler over Israel' (<em>nāgîḏ ʿal yiśrāʾēl</em>) uses the exact covenantal title of Davidic designation. She speaks as a witness to the election that will lead through David's entire reign to the Davidic promise of an eternal throne. The phrase 'all the good he has promised' (<em>kol ʾăšer ḏibbēr YHWH</em>) encapsulates the promise-fulfillment structure of OT eschatology: what YHWH has spoken, he will accomplish. The NT describes Christ's enthronement in exactly these terms: 'The Lord God will give him the throne of his father David, and he will reign over the house of Jacob forever, and of his kingdom there will be no end' (Luke 1:32-33). Abigail is an unwitting prophet of the throne that will not pass away.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The warning against the 'stumbling block' of needless bloodshed and self-vindication is the negative formulation of what 1 Pet 2:23 will describe as Christ's positive practice: 'he committed himself to him who judges justly.' David is warned not to take judgment into his own hands; Christ does not take it into his own hands. The difference is not merely temperamental but ontological: Christ's restraint is the definitive act of cosmic trust in the Father's just judgment, enacted in the face of the world's ultimate injustice. The 'stumbling block' (<em>pûqāh</em>) that Abigail is helping David avoid — the weight of unjustly shed blood — is the burden Christ takes on himself on behalf of others, not the burden he creates through unjust action.</p>",
    "32": "<p>David's blessing of YHWH for sending Abigail 'this day to meet me' acknowledges the providential structure of the encounter — YHWH acting through a human agent to prevent sin and preserve the anointed king's integrity. The pattern of divine provision arriving at the critical moment through an unexpected human agent recurs throughout the salvation history: Jethro's counsel to Moses (Exod 18), the angel's provision for Elijah under the juniper tree (1 Kgs 19:5-8), Joseph's brothers' arrival in Egypt at the moment of famine (Gen 45:5-8). The Christological trajectory points toward the Word itself becoming the decisive provision: 'The Word became flesh and dwelt among us' (John 1:14).</p>",
    "33": "<p>David's blessing of Abigail's <em>ṭaʿm</em> (discernment/good sense) honors the wisdom she embodied in the crisis. The connection to Christ runs through the wisdom tradition: Prov 8 personifies Wisdom as YHWH's companion in creation, and Col 2:3 identifies Christ as the one 'in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge.' Abigail embodies the covenant wisdom that points toward Wisdom incarnate. Her action also demonstrates a structural parallel with the mediation of the Spirit: she arrives at the exact moment, with the exact provision, to turn a violent crisis into reconciliation — the work of the Spirit described in John 16:8-13.</p>",
    "34": "<p>David's counter-factual — 'if you had not come quickly to meet me, not one male would have been left' — acknowledges the nearness of the disaster and the totality of the intervention required. The nearness of catastrophe averted by decisive divine action is a recurring motif in redemption history: the ram caught in the thicket at Moriah (Gen 22:13), the bronze serpent lifted up in the wilderness (Num 21:8), the passover blood on the doorposts (Exod 12:13). The NT identifies Christ as the definitive version of each of these: 'the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world' (John 1:29). Abigail's last-moment arrival is a minor instance of the same structural principle.</p>",
    "35": "<p>David's formal reception of the gift — 'go home in peace, I have heard your voice' — closes the negotiation with a covenant-formula of acceptance. The exchange of provision, intercession, and reconciliation that the chapter has enacted between David and Abigail is a narrative image of what atonement theology describes at the cosmic level: the provision of the mediator received, the judgment stayed, peace pronounced. 'Therefore, since we have been justified by faith, we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ' (Rom 5:1) — the theological form of what Abigail and David enact narratively.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Nabal feasting obliviously 'like a king' while the judgment he cannot see bears down is a portrait of the fool in his final hours. The parable of the rich fool (Luke 12:16-21) follows exactly this structure: the man who has pulled down his barns and built bigger ones, saying to himself 'take your ease, eat, drink, be merry' — and that night his life is required of him. Nabal is a narrative draft of this parabolic type. The theological point is not merely cautionary but christological: the one who accumulates for himself is not 'rich toward God,' and the kingdom announced by Jesus brings this judgment to bear on the self-enclosed economy of the fool.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The stroke that befalls Nabal when Abigail tells him the truth — 'his heart died within him and he became like a stone' — is the narrative judgment on the hardened heart. The stone-heart (<em>lᵉʾāben</em>) recalls Ezekiel's diagnosis and promise: 'I will remove the heart of stone from your flesh and give you a heart of flesh' (Ezek 36:26). Christ's gift of the new covenant is precisely this heart-replacement — but Nabal's heart cannot receive it. The hardening that was his chosen posture becomes, in the moment of truth, his death sentence. The revelation of what the anointed one suffered at his hands is the moment of judgment that cannot be undone.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'The LORD struck Nabal and he died' — divine judgment as the direct execution of covenant consequence. The narrative's attribution of the death to YHWH rather than natural causes places it within the pattern of divine judgment on those who reject YHWH's anointed: Uzzah struck dead for touching the ark (2 Sam 6:7), Ananias and Sapphira struck dead for lying to the Spirit (Acts 5:1-11). The principle in each case is that proximity to the holy without appropriate covenant response brings judgment. Nabal's death is not arbitrary but the structural consequence of refusing the legitimate claim of YHWH's designated king. The NT applies the same pattern to the rejection of Christ: 'How shall we escape if we neglect such a great salvation?' (Heb 2:3).</p>",
    "39": "<p>David's response to Nabal's death — 'Blessed be YHWH who has avenged the insult I received' — is the claim that YHWH executed the judgment David had sought to take with his own sword. Paul's instruction in Romans 12:19-21 — 'do not take revenge, my dear friends, but leave room for God's wrath, for it is written: &ldquo;It is mine to avenge; I will repay,&rdquo; says the Lord' — is the direct NT application of this principle. David's restraint (he did not kill Nabal) and YHWH's action (he did) is the pattern Paul instructs believers to follow, the same pattern Christ enacted on the cross: committing judgment to the Father rather than seizing it. The Christological goal is not that judgment is avoided but that it is administered justly by the one who has the right to administer it.</p>",
    "40": "<p>David's marriage proposal to Abigail, delivered through servants, follows formal covenant protocol. The broader christological significance of the chapter's ending — the anointed king taking a new wife after the destruction of the fool who refused him — is the marital-covenant metaphor that runs through the prophets and into Revelation. The king who was rejected by the wicked and whose enemy is destroyed now draws to himself a covenant partner of wisdom and faithfulness. The image of the Lamb's wedding (Rev 19:7-9 — 'blessed are those who are invited to the marriage supper of the Lamb') is the cosmic realization of this marriage-after-rejection pattern.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Abigail's acceptance formula — volunteering to wash the feet of David's servants — is the posture of the one who enters the covenant relationship with complete self-abasement. Jesus will take this posture with his disciples in the upper room (John 13:5-14: 'If I then, your Lord and Teacher, have washed your feet, you also ought to wash one another's feet'). The symbolic inversion — the wise and beautiful woman offering to perform a slave's service — is the shape of kenotic (self-emptying) love. Abigail's formula anticipates the Christological posture of Incarnation: the great becoming servant of all.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Abigail's rapid response and departure with her five servants reflects the wholehearted covenant response to the anointed king's call. The NT equivalent is the disciples leaving their nets immediately (Matt 4:20 — 'immediately they left their nets and followed him'). The speed and completeness of the response — 'she arose quickly' — is itself a theological marker in the narrative tradition: the right response to the legitimate call of the anointed is decisive, immediate, and total. The kingdom that Christ announces demands the same: 'Leave the dead to bury their own dead. But as for you, go and proclaim the kingdom of God' (Luke 9:60).</p>",
    "43": "<p>The notice of David's other wife, Ahinoam of Jezreel, is a reminder of the narrative complexity of the type. The multiplication of wives is a feature of David's story that stands under the shadow of the Deuteronomic warning to kings (Deut 17:17). The type is not morally perfect; it carries within itself the seeds of the future dysfunction (2 Sam 3:2-5, 13:1-22) that the antitype will not share. Christ is the bridegroom of one bride — the church — in an exclusive and permanent covenant (Eph 5:25-27). The contrast between David's marital complexity and Christ's singular covenant faithfulness is part of the typology's honest structure.</p>",
    "44": "<p>Saul's disposal of Michal — giving her to Palti son of Laish — is an act of power against the anointed that Saul cannot undo. He attempts to sever David's dynastic connection, but the narrative has already established (through Samuel's oracle, Jonathan's covenant, and Abigail's prophecy) that the Davidic dynasty cannot be dissolved by Saul's political maneuvering. The attempted suppression of the anointed is the recurring pattern that culminates in the cross — the ultimate attempt by human power to terminate the Messianic line — which achieves exactly the opposite of its intent. The resurrection is YHWH's reversal of every human attempt to close the door on his anointed king.</p>"
  },
  "26": {
    "1": "<p>The Ziphites' second betrayal of David to Saul represents the persistent hostility of those within Israel who align with the established power against the LORD's chosen. The pattern of insider betrayal — those who should have recognized and protected the anointed instead delivering him to his enemy — reaches its NT culmination in Judas Iscariot, the disciple who guides the arresting party to the garden (John 18:2-3). The betrayals of David in the wilderness are prototypes of the ultimate betrayal: YHWH's anointed handed over by those of his own household to the powers that seek his destruction.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Saul pursues David with 3,000 chosen men into the most inhospitable terrain in the Judean wilderness. The overwhelming disproportion of force — the established king with his entire army against a fugitive with 600 men — is the shape of every unjust persecution of the anointed. The NT will name this disproportion plainly: 'The kings of the earth set themselves, and the rulers were gathered together, against the Lord and against his Anointed (<em>kata tou Kyriou kai kata tou Christou autou</em>)' — Acts 4:26 quoting Ps 2:2. Saul's military pursuit of David in the wilderness is the local enactment of the cosmic hostility that Ps 2 names.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David watches from the wilderness while Saul's camp settles on the hill. Throughout the wilderness period David remains awake, watchful, informed — the posture of the watchman who does not sleep. The messianic Psalms from this period (Pss 34, 57, 63, 142) model this same vigilance: attending to YHWH in the midst of danger, trusting without seeing the full deliverance. The NT develops the eschatological version of this watchfulness: 'What I say to you I say to all: Watch' (Mark 13:37). Christ is himself the watchman who never sleeps over his church (Ps 121:4 — 'he who keeps Israel will neither slumber nor sleep').</p>",
    "4": "<p>David sends scouts and confirms Saul's arrival before acting. The pattern of careful verification before response — not acting on rumor but on confirmed intelligence — is the wisdom posture of the persecuted righteous person. It contrasts with Saul's impulsive decisions throughout his reign (13:9-12, 14:24, 15:15). The theme of the patient observer who gathers intelligence before acting connects to the apocalyptic literature's description of the Son of Man who 'knows the hour' precisely — not acting prematurely, not being caught unprepared. 'The Son of Man is coming at an hour you do not expect' (Matt 24:44) — and conversely, the Son himself acts from perfect knowledge of the Father's timing.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David approaches Saul's camp and observes the layout — identifying where Saul and Abner sleep before descending. The willingness to approach the enemy's innermost position without the intent of violence is the posture of the one who has chosen restraint over retaliation. The Christological parallel is the entry into Jerusalem (Matt 21:1-11) — the anointed king approaching the center of hostile power with full knowledge of what awaits him, not to seize control by force but to demonstrate the character of his kingdom. The approach without violence is itself the proclamation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The composition of David's inner circle at this moment — including Ahimelech the Hittite — is a foretaste of the inclusive community that the Davidic covenant will expand. Non-Israelite warriors within the covenant community of the anointed king points toward the NT reality: 'there is neither Jew nor Greek, there is neither slave nor free, there is no male and female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus' (Gal 3:28). The Messiah gathers to himself not only Israel but individuals from among the nations, even from among former enemies, who recognize his claim and pledge their lives to his cause.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The spear stuck in the ground at Saul's head — the royal emblem exposed and unguarded — is both the vulnerability of the king who has abandoned YHWH and the opportunity that David will not exploit. The unguarded vulnerability of power is a consistent image of the moment when justice could be served by violence but the righteous person refuses it. The NT equivalent is Gethsemane: 'Do you think I cannot call on my Father, and he will at once put at my disposal more than twelve legions of angels?' (Matt 26:53). The weapon of retribution is within reach; it is not taken.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Abishai's offer — 'God has delivered your enemy into your hand today; let me pin him to the ground with one strike' — is the voice of the practical man who sees opportunity and calls it providence. The same argument is made to Jesus in Gethsemane by the disciples who draw swords (Luke 22:50; John 18:10). The immediate practical solution — violence against the identified enemy when access is providentially granted — is the temptation that the anointed must refuse. Jesus's explicit correction — 'No more of this!' (Luke 22:51) and 'put your sword back into its place; for all who take the sword will perish by the sword' (Matt 26:52) — is the definitive form of David's 'Do not destroy him' of v9.</p>",
    "9": "<p>David's principle — 'who can lay a hand on the LORD's anointed and be guiltless?' — names the inviolability of the Messianic commission. The Hebrew <em>Māšîaḥ</em> (anointed) is translated into Greek as <em>Christos</em>: the LORD's anointed is, in its fullest realization, Christ himself. David's refusal to violate the anointing — even Saul's corrupt and rejected version of it — is grounded in a theology of divine appointment that reaches its ultimate expression in the resurrection: no human power can successfully assault the one whom YHWH has anointed, for YHWH vindicates his anointed against every assault. 'The stone the builders rejected has become the cornerstone' (Ps 118:22; Matt 21:42) — the ultimate expression of the inviolability of the divine appointment.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David's three ways YHWH might take Saul — divine judgment, natural death, or death in battle — express a confident theology of divine sovereignty over the timing of justice. The refusal to anticipate or accelerate the divine timeline is the shape of Christ's own waiting for the Father's appointed hour. Throughout John's Gospel Jesus says 'my hour has not yet come' (John 2:4; 7:6, 8, 30; 8:20) and 'my hour has come' (John 12:23; 17:1) — the anointed acts precisely within the Father's appointed time, neither premature nor delayed. David's patience embodies this covenantal trust at the narrative level; Christ embodies it absolutely.</p>",
    "11": "<p>David's oath — 'far be it from me to stretch out my hand against the LORD's anointed' (<em>ḥālîlāh llî</em>) — is the strongest negative commitment available in Hebrew. The oath structure mirrors the NT <em>me genoito</em> ('God forbid,' or 'by no means') that Paul uses in Romans to rule out conclusions that would violate the character of God (Rom 3:4, 6, 31; 6:2, 15; 7:7, 13; 9:14; 11:1, 11). Both are formal repudiations of an action that would be theologically catastrophic. David's refusal to strike Saul despite clear opportunity is the narrative embodiment of Paul's instruction: 'Do not take revenge, my dear friends, but leave room for God's wrath' (Rom 12:19).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The deep sleep from YHWH that fell on Saul's entire camp is divine sovereignty over the sleeping enemy — YHWH creating the conditions for demonstration without permitting violence. The <em>tardēmāh</em> (divine deep sleep) that YHWH sends at critical moments — Adam's sleep at the creation of Eve, Abram's sleep at the covenant ceremony, Saul's camp here — marks moments where YHWH is acting while human consciousness is suspended. The NT equivalent is the disciples' sleep in Gethsemane — but with this reversal: where YHWH sent the sleep to restrain judgment and protect the anointed in the OT, in the NT the disciples' sleep at the critical hour is a failure of watchfulness that the text marks as inadequate ('Could you not watch with me one hour?' Matt 26:40).</p>",
    "13": "<p>David's withdrawal to the opposite ridge before calling out is wisdom operating under self-imposed restraint — he could have escaped silently, but instead he places himself at safe distance and calls out publicly. The decision to make the restraint visible — to demonstrate before witnesses that he had access and chose not to use it — is the pattern of the transparent innocence that the OT anointed maintains before his accusers. Jesus's transparency before the Sanhedrin ('I have spoken openly to the world... I have said nothing in secret,' John 18:20) and before Pilate ('you say that I am a king,' John 18:37) is the ultimate form of this transparent self-presentation that makes the injustice of the persecution undeniable.</p>",
    "14": "<p>David's rebuke of Abner — 'why haven't you guarded your lord the king?' — turns the public confrontation into a demonstration of Abner's dereliction and David's superior faithfulness. The structural inversion — the persecuted fugitive instructing the king's chief officer in his duty — is the pattern of the prophetic rebuke: Nathan confronting David ('you are the man,' 2 Sam 12:7), John the Baptist confronting Herod ('it is not lawful for you to have your brother's wife,' Mark 6:18), Jesus confronting the Pharisees ('you make the word of God of no effect through your tradition,' Matt 15:6). The anointed who speaks the truth to power without protecting himself by silence is the prophetic vocation that Christ embodies completely.</p>",
    "15": "<p>David's indictment of Abner and the camp guard — 'you all deserve to die for not guarding the LORD's anointed' — names the gravity of failing to protect YHWH's designated king. The NT extends this to cosmic proportions: the failure to receive, honor, and protect YHWH's anointed Son carries eschatological weight that David's language only begins to name. 'What will happen to those who do not obey the gospel of God? If it is hard for the righteous person to be saved, what will become of the ungodly and the sinner?' (1 Pet 4:17-18).</p>",
    "16": "<p>The public display of the evidence — 'look where the king's spear and water jug are' — is the exoneration of the innocent performed before witnesses. The anointed king who had access, used it only to take emblems rather than the life, and now presents the evidence publicly is a figure of the transparent innocence that the NT associates with the crucified Christ: 'He committed no sin, neither was deceit found in his mouth' (1 Pet 2:22, citing Isa 53:9). The evidence of David's innocence is visible to all; the evidence of Christ's innocence is the empty tomb.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Saul's recognition of David's voice — 'Is that your voice, David my son?' — is one of the painful recurring ironies of the narrative. Saul addresses the one he has been trying to kill as 'my son' — the covenantal term of paternal care — even while pursuing him through the wilderness. The term anticipates and inverts the Gethsemane cry: where Saul calls his intended victim 'my son' while killing him, the Father addresses his real Son 'this is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased' (Matt 3:17; 17:5) — and the world treats the beloved Son as Saul treated David. The term of deepest love attached to the object of violent pursuit is the narrative's sharpest compression of the Christological paradox.</p>",
    "18": "<p>David's legal self-defense — 'What have I done? What evil is in my hand?' — is repeated across the 1 Samuel narrative (ch. 20, 24, 26) as a formal claim of innocence before the power that persecutes him. The innocent righteous person who must defend his own integrity before an unjust accuser is the shape of Jesus's trial before Pilate: 'What evil has he done? I have found in him no grounds for the death penalty' (Luke 23:22). Pilate is a more reluctant version of Saul — convinced of the accused's innocence but unable or unwilling to stop the process. The formal legal protest of the innocent anointed is a recurring structure that Christ's trial fulfills definitively.</p>",
    "19": "<p>David's appeal — 'if men have stirred you up against me, let them be cursed before the LORD' — invokes the divine curse on those who use slander and accusation to drive the anointed from the covenant land. The theological weight of v19b is the fear that exile from the land means being handed to other gods: 'they have driven me out this day that I should have no share in the heritage of the LORD, saying Go, serve other gods.' Christ's identification with the exiled and the outcast is the incarnational form of this exile: 'He came to his own, and his own people did not receive him' (John 1:11); 'Jesus also suffered outside the gate' (Heb 13:12). The Messiah who is driven out from the covenant center is the pattern of the Incarnation itself.</p>",
    "20": "<p>David's plea against dying 'far from the presence of the LORD' — in a foreign land, away from YHWH's covenantal territory — expresses the OT theology of divine presence as territorially located in the land. The NT's resolution of this is the gift of the Spirit as the permanent presence of YHWH regardless of geography: 'the Spirit of truth, who dwells with you and will be in you' (John 14:17). The Pentecost event undoes the exile-from-presence theology that David fears: no place is 'far from the LORD' for those in whom the Spirit of the resurrected Christ dwells. The Messiah's death outside the city walls (Heb 13:12-13) is itself the act that makes presence-outside-the-sanctuary possible.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Saul's third confession — 'I have sinned' — is the repetition that reveals the pattern of hollow repentance. Saul confesses under public exposure (here, as at 15:24), receives a formal response from David, and returns to his previous behavior. The NT has its own version of this pattern in those who respond to preaching with apparent conviction but whose hearing does not take root: 'the seed that fell on rocky ground — they hear the word and immediately receive it with joy, but they have no root in themselves, but endure for a while, and when tribulation or persecution arises on account of the word, immediately they fall away' (Matt 13:20-21). Saul's recurring confessions are the narrative portrait of the heart that cannot sustain what the mouth confesses.</p>",
    "22": "<p>David's offer to return the spear — without crossing to Saul's side — maintains the legal claim while refusing the reconciliation that would mean surrender to the established power. The spear will remain a symbol of unfinished business between the legitimate and illegitimate holders of power in Israel. The Christological parallel is Jesus's claim before Pilate: 'My kingdom is not of this world. If my kingdom were of this world, my servants would have been fighting, that I might not be delivered over to the Jews. But my kingdom is not from the world' (John 18:36). The claim is made; the surrender to unjust power is refused; the final resolution is left to the Father.</p>",
    "23": "<p>David's closing theological statement — 'the LORD rewards every man for his righteousness and faithfulness' — is the covenant-confidence that makes patient endurance under injustice possible. The NT gives this the resurrection form: 'for the joy that was set before him he endured the cross, despising the shame, and is seated at the right hand of the throne of God' (Heb 12:2). David's trust that YHWH will vindicate the faithful is the shadow; Christ's resurrection is the substance. The reward of righteousness and faithfulness is not merely narrative vindication (as in David's case) but cosmic and eschatological: 'I died, and behold I am alive forevermore' (Rev 1:18).</p>",
    "24": "<p>David's prayer — 'as I valued your life today, may the LORD value my life' — invokes the principle of covenant mutuality: how we treat others determines how we are treated. Jesus makes this explicit: 'with the measure you use it will be measured back to you' (Luke 6:38); 'blessed are the merciful, for they shall receive mercy' (Matt 5:7). David's mercy toward Saul becomes the basis of his prayer for divine mercy toward himself — the same logic that the NT articulates as the connection between human forgiveness and divine forgiveness (Matt 6:12-15). The Christological claim is that Christ's mercy toward sinners is the infinite basis for the infinite mercy they receive: he valued our lives not at the equivalent of his own but far above it — 'God so loved the world that he gave his only Son' (John 3:16).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Saul's final blessing of David — 'you will accomplish great things and will surely prevail' (<em>gam pāʿōl tipʿal</em>) — is an involuntary prophetic concession spoken by the man who has spent the narrative trying to prevent exactly what he is now pronouncing. The one who has been fighting the divine election finally voices it from his own lips. The NT parallel is the high priest Caiaphas's involuntary prophecy: 'it is better for you that one man should die for the people, not that the whole nation should perish... he prophesied that Jesus would die for the nation, and not for the nation only' (John 11:50-52). The enemies of the anointed become, at climactic moments, unwilling vehicles for the divine announcement of his victory.</p>"
  },
  "27": {
    "1": "<p>David's decision to flee to Philistia — born of despair at Saul's persistence — is the low point of his faith in the wilderness period. He acts from a calculation of human probability ('I am going to die by Saul's hand one of these days') rather than the trust he had demonstrated at En-gedi and on the hill of Hachilah. The narrative does not endorse this decision but records its outcome: YHWH will work through even this failure of trust. The theme of divine sovereignty working through flawed human choices — Jacob's deception, Joseph's brothers' envy, Moses's flight to Midian — is consistent across the Pentateuchal narrative. The christological trajectory is not that the types are perfect mirrors of Christ but that YHWH's purposes advance despite and through the type's limitations: 'all things work together for good, for those who are called according to his purpose' (Rom 8:28).</p>",
    "2": "<p>David crosses to Achish at Gath with 600 men. The crossing into Philistine territory — enemy territory, the land of those who had been the covenant people's adversaries since the conquest — is David's voluntary exile from the land of YHWH's promise. The pattern of the elect passing through exile before enthronement runs throughout salvation history: Israel in Egypt, Joseph in prison, Moses in Midian, Elijah hiding at the Wadi Cherith, John the Baptist in the wilderness, Jesus himself in Egypt as an infant (Matt 2:14-15). The period of dwelling in alien territory before the return and enthronement is a consistent type-structure that culminates in Christ's descent into the far country of humanity and death before the resurrection and ascension to the Father's right hand.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David settles among the Philistines with his entire community — men, households, wives. The anointed king living among the nations who do not know YHWH is an image the prophets will develop into the mission theology of the exile: YHWH's servant bearing witness to the nations by his presence among them. Isaiah's Servant songs (particularly Isa 42:1-4 — 'he will bring forth justice to the nations... the coastlands wait for his law') are the prophetic development of the principle that the elect one's presence among the nations is itself the beginning of their inclusion. The Incarnation is the ultimate form of this dwelling-among: 'the Word became flesh and dwelt (<em>eskēnōsen</em>) among us' (John 1:14).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Saul's cessation of pursuit once David has crossed the border demonstrates the limits of the established power's reach. Once the anointed is in the realm of the nations, the domestic power that has been persecuting him loses its ability to threaten. The NT parallel is Jesus's observation about the rejection of prophets in their hometown (Luke 4:24-30) and Paul's strategy of turning to the Gentiles when Jewish opposition makes his mission in a city impossible (Acts 13:46; 18:6). The rejection by one's own people is, paradoxically, the moment when the mission to the nations begins. David's flight to Gath is the precursor to the gospel's journey to the Gentiles.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David requests an outlying town rather than living in the royal city of Gath — maintaining operational distance while formally under Philistine patronage. The theme of the anointed operating in the borderlands, between the covenant people and the nations, is a consistent feature of the pre-enthronement period. John the Baptist's wilderness ministry, Jesus's frequent withdrawal to 'deserted places,' Paul's base of operations in the diaspora synagogues — all embody this border-location that is neither fully inside the established religious center nor outside it. The border is itself a place of proclamation: it reaches those whom the center cannot and will not.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The grant of Ziklag to David 'that day' — and the narrator's note that it belongs to the kings of Judah 'to this day' — is a small but pointed detail of royal continuity: even in the period of David's Philistine exile, the first piece of territory that will belong permanently to the Davidic dynasty is allocated. The kingdom begins as a single outlying town granted by a pagan king, far from Jerusalem and far from the center of Israelite power. The theme of the kingdom starting small and growing is the consistent Christological pattern: the mustard seed (Matt 13:31-32), the leaven in the loaf (Matt 13:33), the single grain of wheat falling into the ground (John 12:24). Ziklag is the mustard seed of the Davidic throne.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The sixteen months of David's Philistine exile — a specific chronological notation — mark a liminal period between promise and fulfillment. The time of waiting in enemy territory, between anointing and enthronement, is the shape of every preparatory period in redemption history. Israel's 430 years in Egypt, Moses's 40 years in Midian, Israel's 40 years in the wilderness, the exile's 70 years in Babylon — all have the same structure: the elect people in the land of the other, under conditions of dependence and obscurity, awaiting the moment of divine intervention and return. Christ's entire earthly life is framed within this liminal structure: born a fugitive (Matt 2:13-14), ministering under Roman occupation, rejected by his own, dying outside the city — until the resurrection reverses every term of the exile.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David's raids against the Geshurites, Girzites, and Amalekites — traditional enemies of Israel on the southern fringe — combine military strategy with a kind of covert covenant faithfulness: he is killing Israel's enemies while appearing to serve Philistia. The theological complexity of this period is part of the narrative's honest portrayal of the type's moral limitations. David is doing something genuinely faithful to Israel (eliminating ancient enemies) through means that involve systematic deception of his patron. The NT does not need to deploy this moral complexity because Christ's mission is not covert: 'I have spoken openly to the world... I have said nothing in secret' (John 18:20). The type's moral ambiguity clarifies by contrast the antitype's moral transparency.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The policy of leaving no survivors — brutal and explicitly noted — is the darkest moment of David's pre-kingship career. The narrative records it without mitigation. This is the honest typology the OT uses: the Davidic figure who will be the vehicle of YHWH's kingdom is also a man capable of systematic violence against civilian populations. The type's moral limitation is the evidence that something greater than David is required. The prophets will name it: 'Behold, the days are coming, declares the LORD, when I will raise up for David a righteous Branch, and he shall reign as king and deal wisely, and shall execute justice and righteousness in the land' (Jer 23:5). The righteous Branch executes justice; he does not execute civilians to maintain his cover story.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David's systematic deception of Achish — reporting false raid targets to maintain the fiction of anti-Israelite activity — is the most morally compromised act of his fugitive career. He is lying to the man who sheltered him, protected him, and trusted him. The narrative does not justify this but records it as part of the liminal period in which the future king is operating under extraordinary constraint. The christological contrast is total: Jesus in similar circumstances of extreme pressure — the temptation in the wilderness, the Sanhedrin trial, the Pilate interrogation — maintains complete truthfulness throughout. 'He committed no sin, neither was deceit found in his mouth' (1 Pet 2:22). The presence of deception in David's record is part of what establishes that he is the type, not the antitype.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The systematic elimination of potential informants — leaving no survivors to carry reports back to Gath — is the logical consequence of the deception: the lie required more violence to sustain it. The compounding of harm through the attempt to maintain falsehood is a structural truth that the wisdom literature diagnoses: 'Whoever conceals his transgressions will not prosper, but he who confesses and forsakes them will obtain mercy' (Prov 28:13). David's Gath period is a narrative illustration of why the final king cannot be David himself: the type operates under moral constraints and moral failures that the antitype must transcend. The sinless obedience of Christ is not an abstract theological claim but the specific correction of the specific failures embedded in the type.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Achish's confident conclusion — that David has permanently alienated himself from Israel and will be Achish's servant forever — is dramatically ironic. He sees the outward appearance of exile and concludes it is permanent; he cannot see that David's return to Israel and enthronement is certain. The same irony governs the enemies of Christ: they seal the tomb ('make it as secure as you can,' Matt 27:65), confident that death has ended the anointed's claim, not knowing that the sealed tomb is the condition of the resurrection morning. The confidence of those who misread the exile as permanent is the foil that makes the return and enthronement more brilliant. 'Why do the nations rage... the one enthroned in heaven laughs; the Lord scoffs at them' (Ps 2:1, 4).</p>"
  }
}

